  "prompt": "How do I change gender in booked IRCTC e-tickets?",
  "response": "Unfortunately, you **cannot directly change the gender** in a booked IRCTC e-ticket after it's been issued. This is a security measure to prevent misuse and maintain the integrity of the booking system.\n\nHere are your options, and why they are limited:\n\n*   **Cancellation and Rebooking (Best Option if Available):**\n\n    *   **The most reliable solution** is to cancel the existing ticket (subject to cancellation charges) and book a new one with the correct gender information.\n    *   **Check Availability:** Before canceling, *immediately* check if tickets are still available for the same train, class, and date. Popular routes can fill up quickly.\n    *   **Cancellation Charges:** Be aware of the cancellation charges, which vary based on the time of cancellation before the scheduled departure.\n    *   **Timing Matters:** If the journey is imminent, cancellation might not be a viable option due to high cancellation fees and the risk of unavailability.\n\n*   **Contact IRCTC Customer Care (Limited Success):**\n\n    *   While IRCTC generally doesn't allow gender changes, it's *worth contacting their customer care* to explain the situation, especially if it was a genuine mistake during booking.\n    *   **Be polite and explain clearly:**  State your PNR number, train number, date of journey, and the correct gender.\n    *   **No Guarantee:**  IRCTC's policy typically prohibits these changes. They *might* be able to guide you on the best course of action, but don't expect a direct fix.\n    *   **How to contact IRCTC:**\n        *   **IRCTC Customer Care Number:** 139 (This is a general railway inquiry number, and they will direct you accordingly)\n        *   **IRCTC E-Ticketing Customer Care:** 0755-6610661, 0755-4090600\n        *   **IRCTC Official Website:** irctc.co.in (Look for the \"Contact Us\" section)\n\n*   **TTE (Travelling Ticket Examiner) at the Station (Least Reliable):**\n\n    *   You *could* try to explain the situation to the TTE on the train or at the boarding station.\n    *   **Risk:** The TTE is *not obligated* to make the change. They may allow you to travel, but they also have the right to refuse travel or impose a penalty.\n    *   **Documentation:** Carry valid photo ID (Aadhar card, PAN card, passport, etc.) that clearly shows your correct gender.\n    *   **Uncertainty:**  Relying on the TTE is highly risky, especially on crowded trains. It's better to explore the other options first.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Accurate Information:** Always double-check all details (name, age, gender, etc.) before confirming your booking.\n*   **Policy Changes:** IRCTC's policies may change, so it's always a good idea to check their official website for the most up-to-date information.\n*   **Transgender Passengers:**  There might be specific guidelines for transgender passengers. Check the IRCTC website or contact customer care for clarification.\n\n**In summary, cancellation and rebooking is the most reliable, but potentially costly, option. Contacting IRCTC is worth a try, but don't expect a guaranteed solution.  Relying on the TTE is the least reliable and should be considered a last resort.**\n",
